{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_roseheath_ver01/data/sn92070146/00414188849/1938010401/0356.xml":{"full_text":"HANK DEBITS\nMONDAY\n$529,354.03\nBUILDING PERMITS\nTO DATE THIS YEAR\nSBOO\nVOLUME XXXVI; No. 261.\nVALLEY FIELD WORKERS STRIKE\nArmed Guards\nTo Protect I. V.\nProduce Trucks\nRambling\neporter\nThe Canal Stamp\u2014\nAll this fuss about trying to get\na postage stamp to commemorate\nthe All American canal\u2019s completion\nreminds us just a little bit of the\nchap who wanted to erect a monu\nment to commemorate the Statue\nof Liberty. Don\u2019t misunderstand.\nIt isn\u2019t that we don\u2019t think the\nstamp\u2019s a good idea. It is merely\nthat we cannot see how anyone can\ndraw 80 miles of canal on a postage\nstamp.\nEven Andy Preble shot short of\nthe mark. He had the grass roots\nconvention in mind, RR suspects,\nwhen he suggested Landon\u2019s pic\nture for the stamp. He should know\nthe canal goes deeper than the\ngrass roots. It goes clear down to\nthe last Nev-Cal stockholder.\nIf they could get a picture of\nEvan Hewes and Mark Rose shak\ning hands, and print it on the\nstamp, they\u2019d sell (10,000 stamps in\nImperial Valley. It would be such\nan unusual stamp.\nIf ever Jim Farley agrees to issue\nthe stamp. RR\u2019ll use several thou\nsand of them\u2014 catching up on cor\nrespondence. It\u2019ll give him at least\none subject to write about the\nstamp.\n\u2014o\nCoincidence\nJust now RR learned that Charles\nHalliday was born on Jan. 1. quite\na few years ago. Anyone who wants\nto can make the remark about a\nHalliday born on a holidav\u2014but RR\nis above that sort of thing.\n\u2014o\nOff With The Old\u2014\nFinally they\u2019re stowing away the\nChristmas street decorations that\nlighted the holiday nights along\nMain street, and now we can get\ndown to the business of 1938. which\ncannot, wait much longer. At that.\nPR's sort of glad to sec the decora\ntions removed. Something the same\nfeeling you have about turkey hash,\nyou know, four days after Christ\nmas.\n\u2014o\u2014\nOn With The New\nSince RR's skin is particularly\nsusceptible to lead poisoning, when\nthe lead comes from a little round\nsteel tube, we shall not mention\nany names here. Suffice it to say\nthat you may see long, curling ring\nlets on many brows where now\nthere is only barren tundra if the\ngadget a group of El Centrans is\nusing accomplishes its purpose\nKnowing the perspiration that\nsprings from bald heads on Im\nperial Valley\u2019s summer days, we\nhave always worried just a mite for\nfear erosion would set in on those\nbrows where there is no foliage to\ncheck the rush of water, but now'\nperhaps we need worry no more.\nThe hair growing device employed\nby the group of El Centro\u2019s select\nmay provide the necessary cultiva\ntion. If it works, RR\u2019s going to\nborrow it for use on his chest.\nMaid Savs Movie\nChain Owner Fed\nHer Poison Food\nIOS ANGELES. Jan. 4. (UP)\u2014\nPolice held James Hostettler. retir\ned lowa theater chain owner, today\non the story told by 19-year-old\nMaria Jimenez after she prepared\nand ate four sandwiches thickly\nspread with poisonous ant paste.\nShe was in critical condition.\nHostettler, 49. was booked at Wil\nshire station on suspicion of crim\ninal assault. He denied the charge.\nThe girl, after eating the poison\nous meal called an attorney, who\nnotified police. She told police she\nhad been assaulted a month ago\nby a guest at the home where she\nis employed as a maid and attempt\ned suicide because she feared for\nher condition.\nStamps Urged to\nCommemorate Canal\nCompletion of the All American\ncanal will be commemorated in a\nspecial issue of government stamps\nif present plans of Imperial Valley\nstamp enthusiasts meet the ap\nproval of federal officials.\nImperial county supervisors Mon\nday approved a project for seeking\nthe i\u2018sue after Henry Harris of El\nCentro described the plan to them.\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS\nSupervisors Act to\nPrevent Union\nInterference\nDemands for a \u201cclosed\nshop\u201d for Imperial Valley\nagriculture Tuesday were\nmet with an order from\ncounty supervisors provid\ning armed convoys for all trucks\ncarrying farm produce to markets.\nA few hours after the order, is\nsued late Monday, Sheriff Robert\nW. Ware had perfected plans to\nsend special deputies with all trucks\nto prevent possible interference\nfrom unions.\nAt the same time, supervisors\nurged all other counties in the\nstate faced by similar threats of\nunion violence, to adopt the convoj\nplan.\nCopies of the resolution will be\nsent to supervisors in every county\nin the state. In particular, the\nboard urged Los Angeles, Kern\nOrange, Riverside, San Francisco,\nSan Bernardino, San Joaquin, Ven\ntura and San Diego counties to\npass similar resolutions, so trucks\nmay reach coast markets without\ninterference.\nOrdered to Organize\nIn explanation of their action,\nboard members said certain farm\ners and transportation companies\nin Imperial county had been or\ndered to follow the \u201cclosed shop\"\nedict. Many farmers own their\ntrucks, the board said, and in or\nder to operate without a loss, drive\nthe trucks themselves. In many\ninstances the farmers would lose\ntheir ranches and suffer financial\nloss if unable to drive their own\n(Continued on Page 8, Col 4)\n20,000 APPLY\nIN STATE FOR\nJOBLESS FUND\nSACRAMENTO. Cal-, Jan. 4 '(J.R)\n\u2014Names of approximately 20.000\njobless Californians were listed\nwith the state unemployment re\nserves commission today for pay\nment of benefits under the Unem\nployment Reserves Act.\nThe big rush for registration of\nImperial county's jobless ended\nbefore noon Tuesday when a total\nof 145 persons had signed for the\nunemployment insurance benefits.\nRussel Bailey, county manager\nfor the State Employment service,\nsaid ho expected the applications\nwill continue but in fewer numbers.\nThe applications are turned over\nto Leo Watts, who has charge of\nthis branch of the service in Im\nperial county. Tlie recommenda\ntions are sent to Sacramento and\nthe payments are made from head\nquarters there.\nCongress Ponders\nBusiness Inquiry\nHOW VARIOUS\nPAPERS REGARD\nF. R. S MESSAGE\nBv UNITED PRESS\nNEW YORK NEWS: On March\n4, 1933, the people listened to Roose\nvelt as a Messiah. Now, we believe,\nmost of them listen to him as a\nman of vast experience and much\ncommon sense. The rest hate his\nguts.\nNEW YORK HERALD-TRIBUNE:\nThe president is hardly at his best\nin discussing basic economic prob\nlems.\nTHE NEW YORK TIMES: By\nand large, the message is reasonable\nin its objectives, praiseworthy in its\ntone and fair in its treatment of\nthose who disagree with specific\npoints in the administration\u2019s pro\ngram.\nNEW YORK SUN: It is disap\npointing to find a sometime disciple\nof economy Trying to pump\nplausibility into an argument that\nexpenditures should be left alone\nuntil receipts\u2014from taxes on the\npeople\u2014can overtake them.\nSCRIPPS-HOWARD NEWSPAP\nERS: Never was a capacity for\nleadership more strikingly demon\nstrated and never in the thick vol\nume of official documents will there\nappear a clearer or more concise\nexpression of policies and purposes.\nCarrying Full UNITED PRESS Day and Niyht Leaned Wire Service and Features of NEA, Inc., Central Press Association, McNauyht Syn\ndicate, King Features, and Complete Valley News Gathered by the Largest Editorial Staff in Southeastern California.\nCrime in Valley to \u2018Qet the Air\u2019\nAn emergency air squad\nron of 10 planes and 15\nqualified pilots to augment\nImperial county\u2019s enforce\nment facilities was propos\ned Monday by Sheriff Rob\nert IP. Ware.\nFifteen vat ley pilots vol\nunteered their services to\nWare in case of emergency\nand the owners of 10 planes\noffered the use of their\nAUTO INJURIES FATAL\nCENTRAL BOY\nFIRST VICTIM\nON 1938 LIST\nHurt Sunday Night as\nHorse Crashed Into\nAutomobile\nLeland Pippin. 17-year-old Cen\ntral High school pupil, became Im\nperial county\u2019s first traffic victim\nfor 1938.\nThe youth died in the El Centro\nhospital at 7:30 o'clock Monday\nnight when he failed to rally after\nan operation. Head injuries, suf\nfered when a runaway horse plung\ned through the windshield of an\nautomobile in which he was rid\ning Sunday night caused his death.\nHe was the only son of Mr. and\nMrs. Sterling Pippin, who operate\na dairy in the Silsbee district. He\nwas a junior at Central union high\nschool, a promising athlete. He was\nborn at Heber and attended Mc-\nCabe elementary school.\nRoosevelt Hopeful\nOf Cooperation\nFrom Nation\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 4.\n(UP)\u2014Close friends of Pres\nident Roosevelt said today\nthe chief executive was hope\nful of a cooperative response\nfrom business to his state-of-the\nnation message as an aid in fight\ning business recession.\nMr. Roosevelt was represented as\nfeeling that the door was open to\nbusiness cooperation with the ad\nministration in meeting the prob\nlems arising from the econonvc\nsituation.\nThe description of White House\nviews was presented as congress\npondered Mr. Roosevelt's message\nand contemplated possibility of a\n(Continued on Page 8, Col. 3)\nCharity Wards, SO,\nHoard SIO.OOO Cache\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 4. (UP)\n\u2014Two little old ladies, both over\n90 years old. rested in a hospi\ntal today unaware that author\nities liad discovered their $lO,-\n000 cache.\nThe secret of the aged spin\nster sisters, who had existed for\nmore than 30 years on contribu\ntions by charity, was discovered\nafter both suffered accidents\nand were taken !o a hospital.\n(Five Cents Per Copy)\nEL CENTRO, CALIF., TUESDAY, JANUARY 4, 1938.\nships in case the sheriff\nneeds to \u201ctake to the air\" in\nmaintaining peace and order\nin the county. Preliminary\narrangements for the emer\ngency squadron were discus\nsed at the board of super\nvisors meeting.\nWare pointed out the ad\nvantage the squadron would\nbe in case of persons lost on\nthe desert. Hours are requir\nLining Up for Unemployment Funds\nAUTO CONCERN\nTO DOUBLE ITS\nWORK FORCES\nDETROIT, Jan. 4 (UP)\u2014Hudson\nMotor Car company announced to\nday it will redouble its present\nworking force and spend $11,000,000\nin the next few weeks in produc\ntion of a new. low-priced automo\nbile.\nTire announcement was made by\nA. B Barit, president of the com\npany. at a special meeting of deal\ners and publishers here.\nTile present working force is 6,-\n000 men, Barit said. This will be\ndoubled and stepped up to full\ntime production, he said, as part of\na plan to \u201cput men and money back\nto work\n\"I: lias become increasingly\nclear to us that with business\nslowing down as it has been re\ncently. we were in a position to do\nmore than announce a new auto\nmobile \u2014we could set the pace in\nthe matter of putting men and\nmoney back to work,\u201d Barit said.\n\u201cWhile there are confidence-in\nspiring moves that can and should\nbe made, the specific job for in\ndustry is to put men and money\nto work.\u201d\nProduction on the new car will\nadd, he estimated, $1,250,000 to the\nHudson monthly payroll,\ned for automobiles to make\nthe search, while one plane\ncould cover the whole area\nin a short time. He said the\nexpense of suc li searches\nwould be reduced by use of\na plane. The squadron will\nbe conside. ee: an emergency\nbranch of the sheriff\u2019s de\npartment and will not be\nused regularly.\nCou n l y supervisors in\n-POST-PRESS PHOTO-ENGRAVING\nMost of Imperial Valley jobless, eligible to receive state unemploy\nment compensation, Tuesday had applid for funds at the Sixth street\noffice of the State Employment service. Russel Bailey, county man\nager. announced 145 had applied by noon Tuesday. Top photo: Lines\nof jobless filing applications. Lower photo: Bailey, right, shown with\nLeo Watts, head of the unemployment insurance division.\nPower Projects\nGet 'Green Light'\nIckes Gives Signal to \u2018Go Ahead\u2019 for\nSixty-One Construction Programs\nAs Result of Court Ruling\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 4. (UP)\u2014Public Works Adminis- j\ntrator Harold L. Ickes grave a \u201cgo ahead\u201d signal to 61 pub\nlie power projects today as a result of a supreme court\ndecision upholding the validity of municipal power plants\nconstructed with PWA funds. The projects will provide\na 100.000,000 man-hour \u201cshot in the*\narm\u201d for industry and will have a\nconstruction cost of $146,917,808.\nThey are located in 23 states.\nIckes promised that the con\nstruction work would be speeded as\nmuch as possible so that the proj\nects could exert a maximum of in\nfluence on unemployment, increas\ned by the business recession.\nThe unanimous court decision in\nthe PWA case was delivered yes\nterday by Justice George Suther\nland. It rejected two attacks on\nthe validity of PWA loans and\ngrants to municipalities for con\nstructioin of power systems-\nThe power projects on which\nconstruction orders are now* being\nissued and the cost of each project\ninclude:\nCalifornia lmperial Irrigation\nDistrict $2,760,000.\nIdaho Coeur d'Alene $729,000.\nNevada Las Vegas $250,909.\nRuling Affects\nState Projects\nSAN FRANCISCO. Jan. 4. (UP)\nSupreme court approval of the con\nstitutionality of public works ad\nministration loans to municipal\nprojects has cleared the way for\nimmediate start on $15,000,000 worth\nof construction projects in Cali\nfornia.\nKenneth A. Godwin, acting PWA\nregional director, said three major\nprojects were affected by the deci\nsion handed down yesterday in\nWashington. They were:\nA 2.750.000 hydro-electric devel\nopment of the All American canal\nnear El Centro to serve the Im\nperial Valley.\nThe $360,000 Redding municipal\nwater supply project.\nThe $12,000,000 Sacramento muni\ncipal power project,\nstructed I) e p ut y District\nAttorney Charles G. Halli\nday to investigate the legal\nangles implicated in the use\nof the squadron.\nWare is considering budg\nes for the squadron mem\nb e r s a n d h a s contacted\nsheriff\u2019s departments i n\nother counties regardng the\nmanagement and utiliza\ntion of airplanes in law en\nforcement work.\nJAPANESE TRY\nDRIVE TO BLOCK\nCHINA RETREAT\nSHANGHAI, Jan. 4. (UP) \u2014Japanese armies drove\nacross rich Shangtung province today in a swift campaign\nagainst Suchow, a railroad junction in northern Kiangsu\nprovince. The Domei (Japanese) news agency reported\nfrom Taian that the Japanese were extending their lines\ntoward the almost devastated city\nof Tsingtao in an effort to cut off\na Chinese retreat.\nIn Tsingtao it was reported that\nthe foreign vigilante organization\nw'ould be disbanded soon as a re\nsult of formation of a Chinese mer\nchants corporation to police the\ncity.\nFrom Canton, in South China,\ncame the report that six Japanese\nairplanes yesterday raided the Chi\nnese Bocca Tigris forts at the\nTwo Arrested in\nRaids Fined SIOO\nWESTMORLAND. Jan. 4.\u2014Glori\nana McShane. 28. and Carmen Ro\ndrigifcz. 26. paid SIOO fines each in\njustice court here Monday after\nconviction of charges of vagrancy.\nThey were arrested Sunday night\nin a vice raid staged by the county\nsheriff\u2019s department. They were\nreleased after payment of the fines\nimposed by Judge U. E. Bailey.\nSixty Filipinos\nQuit, Protest\nToo Much Job'\nLabor\u2019s Latest Attack on Solid Front\nAgainst Unionization Seen in\nWalkout; Violence Averted\nBRAWLEY, Jan. 4\u2014Sixty Filipino harvesters walked\nout of a spinach field south of town early today in what\nis alleged to be labor\u2019s latest attack on Imperial Valley\u2019s\nsolid front against unionization of agriculture.\nSpokesmen for the strikers said there was too much\nwork for them to do and marshall-\"\ned the disgruntled spinach cutters\noff the Sterner Produce company\nfield, Sheriff Robert W. Ware was\ninformed. The peaceful strike was\nblamed upon the activities of men\naccused of being CIO agitators,\nthree of whom are said to have\nbeen working among the men em\nployed by the Sterner company in\na 140 acre spinach field three and\na half miles south of Brawley.\nCary S. Fly of the company dis\nmissed all workers in the field im\nmediately after the walkout, he\nsaid, in order to avoid any clash\nbetween strikers and men who\nwanted to continue work.\nCary then hired a full new crew\nscheduled to begin work on the\nafternoon shift ai 3 o\u2019clock. Cary\nsaid he had not received any com\nplaints other than the discontent\nwith the amount of work.\nFilipinos Held on\nCharge of Slaying\nTwo Countrymen\nTwo Filipinos are held in the\ncounty jail without bail pending\ntheir trial \u00abn charges of murdering\ntwo of their countrymen in El\nCentro Dec. 17.\nCharles Callejo and Pete Ragasa\nmust face trial in superior court on\na charge of slaying Jesus Rabara\nand Leon Navarro in a Broadway\npool hall. Judge John E. Simpson\nof El Centro justice court ordered\nthem without bail following a pre\nliminary hearing Monday.\nHe also ordered three material\nwitnesses. John Recordas, Felix de\nLeon, and Pedro Galo held in jail\nin lieu of $250 bail. Callejo con\nfessed to shooting Navarro and\nRabara as they were eating candy\nin a pool hall. Ragasa is held as\nthe driver of the getaway car.\nSIX KILLED\nIN AIR CRASH\nFRANKFORT, Germany, Jan. 4.\n(UP)\u2014Six persons were killed to\nday when a passenger plane from\nMilan to Frankfort crashed at the\nFrankfort airport, apparently be\ncause of ice forming on the wings.\nThe victims were three German\npassengers, the pilot and two\nmechanics.\nmouth of the Pearl river. The dam\nage was slight.\nBitter fighting was reported to\nhave taken place on the southern\nbank of the Wen river. According\nto Chinese reports a large railway\nbridge over the river had been de\nstroyed.\nSPECIAL AMBULANCE SERVICE\nIN NORTHEND CONTEMPLATED\nSpecial ambulance service for the\nnorth-end of Imperial Valley is ex\npected to follow a conference Mon\nday between members of the coun\nty board of supervisors and repre\nsentatives of the city of Brawley.\nBrawley plans to keep the am\nbulance there and use it for city\nbusiness with the city to stand the\nexpense. When an ambulance is\nneeded in county territory in the\nnorth-end the Brawley ambulance\nwould answer the call with the\nunderstanding that the county pay\nButter: Low Angeles, J3',c;\nterfat. Imperial Valley, of..b. ranch\ngrade A. 43 1 jc; manufacturing milk\n36',2C; route gathered cream, 33r,\nL. A. Hay: U. S. No. I *16.50-\n19.50: No. 2 leafy. *l7-17.50; No.\n2 leafy, sl6-16.50.\nMinneapolis flax. May, *2.02.\nPHONE 300\nHUGH OSBORNE\nHEADS COUNTY\nSUPERVISORS\nValley Banker, Rancher\nNamed in Unanimous\nBallot of Board\nHugh T. Osborne of El\nCentro Tuesday headed the\nImperial county board of su\npervisors following the an\nnual election Monday.\nHe was elected by a unanimous\nvote to occupy the office held by\nIsaac Schlatter of Calexico in 1936\nand 1937.\nAll county employes were reap\npointed and Supervisor Dave Ven\ncill of Holtviile was reappointed\nchairman of the committee gov\nerning the county farm and hos\npital.\nOsborne was elected supervisor\nin Jan, 1933 and was reelected for\na second term at the last county\nelection. He came to Imperial Val\nley in 1919 because his physician\nrecommended the climate as bene\nficial to world war wounds. He has\nbeen engaged in the vegetable bus\niness, in banking, in building and\nloan, and ranching. He is manager\nof the Associated Farmers of Im\nperial county.\nAfter the election Monday, the\nboard rejected all bids submitted\nfor the county gasoline contract\nfor the coming year and called for\nnew bids to be opened at the next\nmeeting, Jan. 17. The contract calls\nfor an approximate delivery of 10,-\n000 gallons a month for use at\nschool district headquarters, road\ndistrict headquarters, the county\ngarage, and the county farm and\nhospital. The board decided they\ncould save the county money by\ndemanding new bids.\nWESTMORLAND\nJUDGE, OUSTED,\nIS REINSTATED\nWESTMORLAND, Jan. 4.\u2014West\nmorland\u2019s political serenity with\nstood another violent upheaval\nMonday night when Sam P. Rowe\nresigned as city councilman and\nimmediately was appointed police\njudge, a position from which he\nwas ousted last July.\nCity hall had not stopped rock\ning after U. E. Bailey, justice of\nthe peace, was discharged from\nthe position of city judge when\nRowe\u2019s resignation was read. Bailey\nwas appointed police judge in last\nsummer\u2019s political furore and had\nserved since that time in the dual\nposition.\nThe council then counted noses\nand discovered two men were miss\ning. The appointment of John J.\nGardner was made to fill the va\ncancy left by a recent resignation\noi F. J. Clevenger. No further ap\npointments were made This left\nthe board one man short, a condi\ntion which has prevailed since Oc\ntober when three men resigned in\nquick succession.\nGardner is a cook and has lived\nin Westmorland for 12 years. This\nis his first municipal appointment\nWestmorland\u2019s city councilmen\nconsists of Mayor B. H Evans and\nCouncilmen J. B Miller, C. E\nWaugh, and Gardner\ngasoline mileage.\nThis arrangement is contemplat\ned because of the distance the\ncounty ambulance must travel from\nthe county hospital to the northern\nareas of the county. The service\nwould result in injured persons be\ning taken to hospitals or physicians\nwith the least possible delay When\nBrawley maintained such an am\nbulance several years ago, 85 per\ncent of the business was county\nbusiness, the board was Informed\nFurther details are to be discussed\nat the meeting Jan 17.\nTHE POST-PRESS","height":"29632","width":"23228"}}
